ve slope α \\alpha and locally enforces zero mean and unit variance constraints to mitigate gradient vanishing. The activation is defined as: (12) Φ ​ ( u ) = SSLReLU ​ ( u ) = s ⋅ h ​ ( u ) + b , \\Phi(u)=\\text{SSLReLU}(u)=s\\cdot h(u)+b, where h ​ ( u ) = sgn ​ ( u ) ⋅ ( LeakyReLU α ​ ( u ) ) 2 h(u)=\\text{sgn}(u)\\cdot(\\text{LeakyReLU}_{\\alpha}(u))^{2} is the signed squared transformation. Parameters s s and b b stabilize signal propagation. Normalization Constants. Assuming the normalized input follows a standard normal distribution u ∼ 𝒩 ​ ( 0 , 1 ) u\\sim\\mathcal{N}(0,1) , we derive closed form solutions for s s and b b . Using Gaussian symmetry where the contribution of each half space to the k k -th moment is 1 2 ​ μ k \\frac{1}{2}\\mu_{k} with μ 2 = 1 \\mu_{2}=1 and μ 4 = 3 \\mu_{4}=3 , the moments of h ​ ( u ) h(u) are calculated as: (13) 𝔼 ​ [ h ​ ( u ) ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[h(u)] = 1 2 ​ μ 2 ⏟ positive + 1 2 ​ ( − α 2 ) ​ μ 2 ⏟ negative = 1 − α 2 2 , \\displaystyle=\\underbrace{\\frac{1}{2}\\mu_{2}}_{\\text{positive}}+\\underbrace{\\frac{1}{2}(-\\alpha^{2})\\mu_{2}}_{\\text{negative}}=\\frac{1-\\alpha^{2}}{2}, (14) 𝔼 ​ [ h ​ ( u ) 2 ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[h(u)^{2}] = 1 2 ​ μ 4 ⏟ positive + 1 2 ​ ( − α 2 ) 2 ​ μ 4 ⏟ negative = 3 ​ ( 1 + α 4 ) 2 . \\displaystyle=\\underbrace{\\frac{1}{2}\\mu_{4}}_{\\text{positive}}+\\underbrace{\\frac{1}{2}(-\\alpha^{2})^{2}\\mu_{4}}_{\\text{negative}}=\\frac{3(1+\\alpha^{4})}{2}. To strictly enforce the unit variance property, the normalization constants are determined by: (15) s = 1 𝔼 ​ [ h ​ ( u ) 2 ] − ( 𝔼 ​ [ h ​ ( u ) ] ) 2 , b = − s ⋅ 𝔼 ​ [ h ​ ( u ) ] . s=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mathbb{E}[h(u)^{2}]-(\\mathbb{E}[h(u)])^{2}}},\\quad b=-s\\cdot\\mathbb{E}[h(u)]. These constants counteract the distribution shift. Table 3 . Efficiency Comparison Methods Inference Time (ms) UMMAFormer ( ref36 , ) 29850 EVAS 57 EVAS (Lightweight) 50 Efficiency Analysis. We evaluate the efficiency of our approach under strictly identical experimental settings. Experimental results demonstrate that our lightweight EVAS method requires only 50ms for the inference of a single video, whereas the UMMAFormer baseline (including the feature extraction component) takes 29850ms. Furthermore, at the module level, by substituting the wide-expansion FFN with our proposed lightweight HourglassFFN architecture, the total inference time on the validation set is reduced from 1499s to 1316s. This corresponds to a latency reduction of approximately 12.2%. These results demonstrate that the efficiency gains derived from reduced memory access and parameter count effectively outweigh the computational overhead introduced by the activation function. Table 4 . Comparison of the performance of various methods on the TVIL dataset. Bold values denote the best performance, underlined values denote the second-best performance, and the E2E column indicates whether the model is trained in an end-to-end manner. Methods Features E2E AP @ @ 0.5 AP @ @ 0.75 AP @ @ 0.95 mAP AR @ @ 10 AR @ @ 20 AR @ @ 50 AR @ @ 100 TAGS ( ref54 , ) Visual × \\times 18.40 12.68 0.09 10.39 24.41 25.05 25.56 25.56 DCAN ( ref55 , ) Visual × \\times 82.75 75.00 3.22 53.66 64.73 66.02 68.82 69.97 ActionFormer ( ref35 , ) Visual × \\times 86.27 83.03 28.17 65.82 84.82 85.77 88.10 88.49 UMMAFormer ( ref36 , ) Visual × \\times 88.68 84.70 62.43 78.60 87.09 88.21 90.43 91.16 EVAS Visual ✓ \\checkmark 94.91 93.16 62.56 83.54 91.96 92.39 93.25 94.03 Table 5 . Ablation study on the effectiveness of key components. A+V: Audio-Visual Baseline; BAR: Boundary-Aware Refinement; MAVS: Multi-Stage Audio-Visual Synergy. A+V BAR MAVS AP @ @ 0.5 AP @ @ 0.75 AP @ @ 0.95 mAP AR @ @ 10 AR @ @ 20 AR @ @ 50 AR @ @ 100 ✓ ✗ ✗ 97.78 95.83 83.96 92.52 96.40 96.54 96.63 96.73 ✓ ✓ ✗ 98.68 96.95 88.25 94.63 97.56 97.63 97.71 97.78 ✓ ✓ ✓ 98.41 96.61 88.63 94.55 97.59 97.67 97.73 97.81 Table 6 . Analysis of the number of attention layers in the Multi-Stage Audio-Visual Synergy module. Layers ( L L ) AP @ @ 0.5 AP @ @ 0.75 AP @ @ 0.95 mAP AR @ @ 10 AR @ @ 20 AR @ @ 50 AR @ @ 100 0 98.68 96.95 88.25 94.63 97.56 97.63 97.71 97.78 1 1 97.53 95.27 77.43 90.08 95.15 95.32 95.48 95.62 2 2 98.41 96.61 88.63 94.55 97.59 97.67 97.73 97.81 3 3 97.34 95.26 76.66 89.75 95.02 95.16 95.31 95.44 3.5. Inference and Loss During the inference phase, we strictly adhere to the decoupled training inference strategy detailed in Section 4.3. The training objective incorporates both class", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec/tool-results/b1m5xmlvi.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 50564}}
