{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783858284749", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-b9ac7129f29e9407", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "curl -sL \"https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.04498\" 2>&1 | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, re\nhtml = sys.stdin.read()\nm = re.search(r'property=\\\"og:description\\\" content=\\\"([^\\\"]+)\\\"', html)\nif m: print('ABSTRACT:', m.group(1)[:3000])\nm2 = re.search(r'citation_title\\\" content=\\\"([^\\\"]+)\\\"', html)\nif m2: print('TITLE:', m2.group(1))\nm3 = re.search(r'citation_online_date\\\" content=\\\"([^\\\"]+)\\\"', html)\nif m3: print('DATE:', m3.group(1))\n\" 2>&1", "description": "Fetch UniSkip-Mamba paper details", "timeout": 15000}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec", "uuid": "9ad76258-6aa2-465f-b23c-248169f93cd0"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b9ac7129f29e9407", "type": "tool_result", "content": "ABSTRACT: With the proliferation of AI-generated content, sophisticated multimedia manipulation has raised critical concerns about malicious applications such as opinion manipulation and evidence fabrication, making Audio-Visual Temporal Forgery Localization (AV-TFL) an urgent research frontier. Existing TFL methods have progressed along two main paradigms: Transformer-based temporal modeling and channel-wise multimodal fusion. While these approaches capture temporal dependencies and cross-modal correlations, they process all frequency components indiscriminately, leading to overfitting on high-frequency noise and limited robustness under real-world data degradation. Through systematic frequency domain analysis, we find that forgery-discriminative patterns concentrate in the low/mid-frequency range (normalized frequency 0-0.15), while high-frequency components primarily introduce noise, removing them even improves detection performance by +1.4%. Based on this phenomenon, we propose UniSkip-Mamba, a frequency-aware State Space Model framework that incorporates Unified Multimodal Sequence Fusion to preserve cross-modal phase relationships, and Skip-Scanning Mamba Blocks that implement frequency-aware regularization through a novel Group-Scan-Merge mechanism, naturally biasing learning toward discriminative low/mid-frequency patterns (0-0.15) while maintaining representational completeness. We achieve state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance: 63.4% AP@0.95 on LAV-DF (+9.8% improvement) and 63.58% mAP on AV-Deepfake1M (+14.32% improvement), with 6x faster inference. Our frequency-domain analysis provides theoretical justification from a signal processing perspective for why skip-scanning inherently improves both accuracy and robustness.\nTITLE: UniSkip-Mamba: A Frequency-Aware State Space Model for Audio-Visual Temporal Forgery Localization\nDATE: 2026/07/05", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec", "uuid": "a4393087-01d0-4fbc-9088-6c755c3603db", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T12:11:28.815Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "ABSTRACT: With the proliferation of AI-generated content, sophisticated multimedia manipulation has raised critical concerns about malicious applications such as opinion manipulation and evidence fabrication, making Audio-Visual Temporal Forgery Localization (AV-TFL) an urgent research frontier. Existing TFL methods have progressed along two main paradigms: Transformer-based temporal modeling and channel-wise multimodal fusion. While these approaches capture temporal dependencies and cross-modal correlations, they process all frequency components indiscriminately, leading to overfitting on high-frequency noise and limited robustness under real-world data degradation. Through systematic frequency domain analysis, we find that forgery-discriminative patterns concentrate in the low/mid-frequency range (normalized frequency 0-0.15), while high-frequency components primarily introduce noise, removing them even improves detection performance by +1.4%. Based on this phenomenon, we propose UniSkip-Mamba, a frequency-aware State Space Model framework that incorporates Unified Multimodal Sequence Fusion to preserve cross-modal phase relationships, and Skip-Scanning Mamba Blocks that implement frequency-aware regularization through a novel Group-Scan-Merge mechanism, naturally biasing learning toward discriminative low/mid-frequency patterns (0-0.15) while maintaining representational completeness. We achieve state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance: 63.4% AP@0.95 on LAV-DF (+9.8% improvement) and 63.58% mAP on AV-Deepfake1M (+14.32% improvement), with 6x faster inference. Our frequency-domain analysis provides theoretical justification from a signal processing perspective for why skip-scanning inherently improves both accuracy and robustness.\nTITLE: UniSkip-Mamba: A Frequency-Aware State Space Model for Audio-Visual Temporal Forgery Localization\nDATE: 2026/07/05", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783858313425", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "这是一篇关键发现！**UniSkip-Mamba** (arXiv 2607.04498，与 EVAS 同日提交) 在相同的数据集上取得了 SOTA 结果：\n- LAV-DF: AP@0.95 = 63.4% (相比之下 EVAS 为 88.63%)\n- AV-Deepfake1M: mAP = 63.58% (相比之下 EVAS 为 70.20%)\n\n等等——EVAS 的数据明显更好。但 UniSkip-Mamba 声称“+9.8% improvement”和“+14.32% improvement”达到了 SOTA。这表明它们对比的可能是不同的基线，或者使用了不同的评估协议。让我记录下这一点，并核对一下 ICCV 2025 的同步处理论文。"}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec", "uuid": "e89e383c-9229-4104-8693-c8ed4bb503f2"}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783858313425", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-80711370d02e504c", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "# Check the ICCV 2025 intra/cross-modal sync paper\ncurl -sL \"https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/ICCV2025/papers/Anshul_Intra-modal_and_Cross-modal_Synchronization_for_Audio-visual_Deepfake_Detection_and_Temporal_ICCV_2025_paper.pdf\" -o /tmp/iccv2025_sync.pdf 2>&1 && python3 -c \"\nimport subprocess\nresult = subprocess.run(['pdftotext', '/tmp/iccv2025_sync.pdf', '-'], capture_output=True, text=True)\ntext = result.stdout[:8000]\nprint(text)\n\" 2>&1", "description": "Fetch ICCV 2025 sync paper for comparison", "timeout": 30000}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec", "uuid": "165f157b-2a34-48d0-8610-9a85c5b6fc1a"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-80711370d02e504c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "This ICCV paper is the Open Access version, provided by the Computer Vision Foundation.\nExcept for this watermark, it is identical to the accepted version;\nthe final published version of the proceedings is available on IEEE Xplore.\n\nIntra-modal and Cross-modal Synchronization for Audio-visual Deepfake\nDetection and Temporal Localization\nAshutosh Anshul, Shreyas Gopal, Deepu Rajan, and Eng Siong Chng\nCollege of Computing and Data Science, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore\n{ashutosh007, shreyas011}@e.ntu.edu.sg, {asdrajan, aseschng}@ntu.edu.sg\n\nAbstract\nRecent deepfake detection algorithms focus solely on\nuni-modal or cross-modal inconsistencies. While the former disregards audio-visual correspondence entirely rendering them less effective against multimodal attacks, the\nlatter overlooks inconsistencies in a particular modality.\nMoreover, many models are single-stage supervised frameworks, effective on specific training data but less generalizable to new manipulations. To address these gaps, we\npropose a two-stage multimodal framework that first learns\nintra-modal and cross-modal temporal synchronization on\nreal videos, capturing audio-visual correspondences crucial for deepfake detection and localization. We introduce\na Gaussian-targeted loss in our pretraining model to focus\non learning relative synchronization patterns across multimodal pairs. Using pretrained features, our approach not\nonly enables classification on fully manipulated videos but\nalso supports a localization module for partial deepfakes\nwith only specific segments spoofed. Moreover, the pretraining stage does not require fine-tuning, thus reducing complexity. Our model, tested on various benchmark datasets,\ndemonstrates strong generalization and precise temporal\nlocalization.1\n\nnipulations of either or both audio and visual content are\ngaining traction [19, 28, 40]. It is also possible that only a\nspecific section or non-contiguous parts of a video or audio\nare manipulated [7–9, 14]. In this case, the task requires\nprecise localization of the manipulations as opposed to a\nsimple detection, which is a binary classification problem.\nIn this work, we present a multimodal approach for deepfake detection and temporal localization. Previous works\non learning joint audio-visual cues for multimodal deepfake detection use early or intermediate fusion [2, 53, 59] or\nlate fusion [29, 47, 60] of audio and visual features. Some\nstudies have incorporated contrastive loss to enhance the\nlearning of audio-visual correspondence, highlighting differences between real audio-video pairs and deepfakes [37,\n53]. Most of these models are single-stage supervised models trained directly on a specific deepfake dataset such as\nFake AVCeleb [28]. While such models achieve promising performance, [40] asserts that a single-stage supervised\ntraining may limit the model’s ability to explore audiovisual consistencies thoroughly and could lead to the learning of features that are too specific to the training dataset,\nimpairing generalization to unseen manipulations and data\ndistributions. On the other hand, the cross-generalization\nperformance of some recent works [19, 24, 40] suggest\nthat pretraining the model on real samples using multimodal learning may enhance the identification of intuitive\naudio-visual inconsistencies, which can then be leveraged\nfor more effective deepfake detection.\nIn this work, we propose a two-stage training framework\nthat first learns intra-modal and cross-modal temporal synchronization in real videos and then uses the inferred features from the pretraining stage for deepfake classification\nor localization. Intra-modal temporal synchronization of a\nsegment in a video or audio refers to the continuity of visual or audio frames, which should be highest with that\nof its previous or the next segment. Cross-modal temporal synchronization aims to predict how likely a segment\nof video aligns temporally with an audio segment. While\nthe classification and localization models are two different\narchitectures, they both use features learned by the same\n\n1. Introduction\nAdvancements in generative modeling have led to the creation of highly realistic images, videos, and audio. While\nsuch generated content has applications in fields like entertainment and education, they are more often used maliciously to commit fraud and spread misinformation. Deepfake detection models are being developed, especially those\nthat can generalize over unseen manipulations and diverse\ndata distributions. While many of these deepfake detectors focus on a single modality such as image, video, or\naudio [23, 24, 43], multimodal approaches that detect ma1 Code - https://github.com/AshutoshAnshul/ics-avdeepfake\n\n13826\n\n\fpretraining model. Inspired by Feng et al. [19], our pretraining model learns temporal synchronization and does\nnot require any fine-tuning in the second stage. However,\ndifferent from [19], we propose to use three synchronization models - two focused on intra-modal synchronization\nand one on cross-modal synchronization. This enables the\nmodel to jointly learn intra-modal and cross-modal consistencies during classification and localization. Additionally,\nwe propose two variants of an attention model that can predict frame-level synchronization. The variants adopt local\nattention and are also focused on reducing model complexity by replacing self-attention with convolution-based attention. Finally, the pretraining model computes its loss with\nthe proposed Gaussian targets aimed at learning the relative synchronization between multiple audio-video, videovideo, or audio-audio segment pairs (discussed in Sec. 3.1).\nWe evaluate our approach against existing methods\nacross multiple datasets and various settings. Our model’s\nperformance is comparable to state-of-the-art approaches. It\nis also able to generalize across unseen manipulations and\ndifferent deepfake datasets. It leverages temporal continuity and synchronization during pretraining to capture both\nintra-modal and cross-modal consistencies, enabling the detection of inconsistencies within and between modalities for\ndeepfake classification and temporal localization tasks. In\nsummary:\n• We propose a synchronization-based pretraining model\nthat learns intra-modal and cross-modal temporal correspondence in real videos. Our pretraining model does not\nrequire any task-specific finetuning and its inference can\nbe used for deepfake detection and temporal localization.\n• We propose two attention models in the synchronization\nframework: (i) decoder variant and (ii) sparse encoder\nvariant, and show that the latter achieves comparable performance with faster training.\n• We design Gaussian targets to compute loss for the pretraining model to effectively learn the relative synchronization between intra-modal or cross-modal segment\npairs. Ablation studies show that the proposed targets\nhelp the model achieve better performance compared to\nInfoNCE loss [39].\n• Our overall two-stage model can achieve comparable performance on deepfake detection datasets. It can also\ngeneralize over unseen manipulations and diverse dataset\ndistribution. We also show that the features inferred by\nthe synchronization model can also be utilized to localize\npartial deepfakes.\n\n2. Related Works\n2.1. Deepfake Detection\nVisual only approaches: Numerous approaches have\naimed at detecting facial manipulations. Some methods\n\naim to identify artifacts in texture [35, 57], frequency domain [22, 26, 36], and blending [32]. Other approaches\nlook at temporal [13, 20, 58] and spatiotemporal inconsistencies [41, 49, 55]. [43] trains XceptionNet, a convolutionbased network, setting up a benchmark for their proposed\ndataset FaceForensics++. LipForensics [23] proposes a\ngeneralizable deepfake detection algorithm that identifies\nlip movement irregularities in deepfakes. Zheng et al. propose FTCN [58], a two-stage end-to-end network comprising a convolution network followed by a transformer to\nexplore faci", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f1afa3c-9afd-4bb5-8422-81762cbc98ec", "uuid": "b956d649-a369-47cf-99ba-97f641fb35cb", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T12:12:05.547Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "This ICCV paper is the Open Access version, provided by the Computer Vision Foundation.\nExcept for this watermark, it is identical to the accepted version;\nthe final published version of the proceedings is available on IEEE Xplore.\n\nIntra-modal and Cross-modal Synchronization for Audio-visual Deepfake\nDetection and Temporal Localization\nAshutosh Anshul, Shreyas Gopal, Deepu Rajan, and Eng Siong Chng\nCollege of Computing and Data Science, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore\n{ashutosh007, shreyas011}@e.ntu.edu.sg, {asdrajan, aseschng}@ntu.edu.sg\n\nAbstract\nRecent deepfake detection algorithms focus solely on\nuni-modal or cross-modal inconsistencies. While the former disregards audio-visual correspondence entirely rendering them less effective against multimodal attacks, the\nlatter overlooks inconsistencies in a particular modality.\nMoreover, many models are single-stage supervised frameworks, effective on specific training data but less generalizable to new manipulations. To address these gaps, we\npropose a two-stage multimodal framework that first learns\nintra-modal and cross-modal temporal synchronization on\nreal videos, capturing audio-visual correspondences crucial for deepfake detection and localization. We introduce\na Gaussian-targeted loss in our pretraining model to focus\non learning relative synchronization patterns across multimodal pairs. Using pretrained features, our approach not\nonly enables classification on fully manipulated videos but\nalso supports a localization module for partial deepfakes\nwith only specific segments spoofed. Moreover, the pretraining stage does not require fine-tuning, thus reducing complexity. Our model, tested on various benchmark datasets,\ndemonstrates strong generalization and precise temporal\nlocalization.1\n\nnipulations of either or both audio and visual content are\ngaining traction [19, 28, 40]. It is also possible that only a\nspecific section or non-contiguous parts of a video or audio\nare manipulated [7–9, 14]. In this case, the task requires\nprecise localization of the manipulations as opposed to a\nsimple detection, which is a binary classification problem.\nIn this work, we present a multimodal approach for deepfake detection and temporal localization. Previous works\non learning joint audio-visual cues for multimodal deepfake detection use early or intermediate fusion [2, 53, 59] or\nlate fusion [29, 47, 60] of audio and visual features. Some\nstudies have incorporated contrastive loss to enhance the\nlearning of audio-visual correspondence, highlighting differences between real audio-video pairs and deepfakes [37,\n53]. Most of these models are single-stage supervised models trained directly on a specific deepfake dataset such as\nFake AVCeleb [28]. While such models achieve promising performance, [40] asserts that a single-stage supervised\ntraining may limit the model’s ability to explore audiovisual consistencies thoroughly and could lead to the learning of features that are too specific to the training dataset,\nimpairing generalization to unseen manipulations and data\ndistributions. On the other hand, the cross-generalization\nperformance of some recent works [19, 24, 40] suggest\nthat pretraining the model on real samples using multimodal learning may enhance the identification of intuitive\naudio-visual inconsistencies, which can then be leveraged\nfor more effective deepfake detection.\nIn this work, we propose a two-stage training framework\nthat first learns intra-modal and cross-modal temporal synchronization in real videos and then uses the inferred features from the pretraining stage for deepfake classification\nor localization. Intra-modal temporal synchronization of a\nsegment in a video or audio refers to the continuity of visual or audio frames, which should be highest with that\nof its previous or the next segment. Cross-modal temporal synchronization aims to predict how likely a segment\nof video aligns temporally with an audio segment. While\nthe classification and localization models are two different\narchitectures, they both use features learned by the same\n\n1. Introduction\nAdvancements in generative modeling have led to the creation of highly realistic images, videos, and audio. While\nsuch generated content has applications in fields like entertainment and education, they are more often used maliciously to commit fraud and spread misinformation. Deepfake detection models are being developed, especially those\nthat can generalize over unseen manipulations and diverse\ndata distributions. While many of these deepfake detectors focus on a single modality such as image, video, or\naudio [23, 24, 43], multimodal approaches that detect ma1 Code - https://github.com/AshutoshAnshul/ics-avdeepfake\n\n13826\n\n\fpretraining model. Inspired by Feng et al. [19], our pretraining model learns temporal synchronization and does\nnot require any fine-tuning in the second stage. However,\ndifferent from [19], we propose to use three synchronization models - two focused on intra-modal synchronization\nand one on cross-modal synchronization. This enables the\nmodel to jointly learn intra-modal and cross-modal consistencies during classification and localization. Additionally,\nwe propose two variants of an attention model that can predict frame-level synchronization. The variants adopt local\nattention and are also focused on reducing model complexity by replacing self-attention with convolution-based attention. Finally, the pretraining model computes its loss with\nthe proposed Gaussian targets aimed at learning the relative synchronization between multiple audio-video, videovideo, or audio-audio segment pairs (discussed in Sec. 3.1).\nWe evaluate our approach against existing methods\nacross multiple datasets and various settings. Our model’s\nperformance is comparable to state-of-the-art approaches. It\nis also able to generalize across unseen manipulations and\ndifferent deepfake datasets. It leverages temporal continuity and synchronization during pretraining to capture both\nintra-modal and cross-modal consistencies, enabling the detection of inconsistencies within and between modalities for\ndeepfake classification and temporal localization tasks. In\nsummary:\n• We propose a synchronization-based pretraining model\nthat learns intra-modal and cross-modal temporal correspondence in real videos. Our pretraining model does not\nrequire any task-specific finetuning and its inference can\nbe used for deepfake detection and temporal localization.\n• We propose two attention models in the synchronization\nframework: (i) decoder variant and (ii) sparse encoder\nvariant, and show that the latter achieves comparable performance with faster training.\n• We design Gaussian targets to compute loss for the pretraining model to effectively learn the relative synchronization between intra-modal or cross-modal segment\npairs. Ablation studies show that the proposed targets\nhelp the model achieve better performance compared to\nInfoNCE loss [39].\n• Our overall two-stage model can achieve comparable performance on deepfake detection datasets. It can also\ngeneralize over unseen manipulations and diverse dataset\ndistribution. We also show that the features inferred by\nthe synchronization model can also be utilized to localize\npartial deepfakes.\n\n2. Related Works\n2.1. Deepfake Detection\nVisual only approaches: Numerous approaches have\naimed at detecting facial manipulations. Some methods\n\naim to identify artifacts in texture [35, 57], frequency domain [22, 26, 36], and blending [32]. Other approaches\nlook at temporal [13, 20, 58] and spatiotemporal inconsistencies [41, 49, 55]. [43] trains XceptionNet, a convolutionbased network, setting up a benchmark for their proposed\ndataset FaceForensics++. LipForensics [23] proposes a\ngeneralizable deepfake detection algorithm that identifies\nlip movement irregularities in deepfakes. Zheng et al. propose FTCN [58], a two-stage end-to-end network comprising a convolution network followed by a transformer to\nexplore faci", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
